  "sourceNotes": "Cassata siciliana has its origins in Arab-influenced Sicilian sweets from the medieval period and is documented in Sicilian and Italian culinary literature from at least the sixteenth century. Pellegrino Artusi, La Scienza in Cucina e l'Arte di Mangiar Bene (1891, freely available at Project Gutenberg IT), describes cassata as a Sicilian preparation. The layered sponge, ricotta, and marzipan format with fondant icing is described in Italian baking guides and Sicilian domestic manuals published before 1928.",
